Eating Disorders and the Beauty Myth
	As children grow older, they become more aware and self-conscious of themselves and their bodies. Many times, this is a negative experience, as children begin to compare themselves against their peers, models in magazines, and modern beauty standards. This can be damaging to both mental and physical health, as such comparisons can lead to the development of eating disorders like anorexia, bulimia, and binge eating. Despite being subjected to similar media and peer groups, eating disorders disproportionately affect young women and girls as opposed to young men and boys. (This is not to say that males are not affected by eating disorders). This brings many to raise the following question: Why do women, young women particularly, get diagnosed with eating disorders so much more frequently than men? The answer to this question is based on how society highly values the way that a woman looks, above all other personal aspects, and does not hold men up to the same standard. Because a woman’s value is seemingly determined by her looks, a phenomenon known as the beauty myth, eating disorders plague younger women and girls and can cause severe mental and physical consequences. 
	In my personal experience, eating disorders are incredibly common in my peers. I have distinct memories of sitting at the lunch table with friends in my middle and high school years discussing how we could lose weight, apply makeup, or utilize a number of other beauty treatments. This was characterized by normal “girl talk”, while boys in the seats across the room were more concerned with whose soccer team they would be on at recess than anything else. Even now as a college student, I frequently witness similar interactions among my peers, specifically in the swim team locker room. Before anyone that I knew was ever diagnosed with an eating disorder, it was commonplace for us all to despise and attempt to improve upon our naturally growing and changing bodies. This age and time period are universally awkward for children as they go through puberty and their body transitions into something new and unknown. This is an incredibly vulnerable and developmentally important time period and the diagnosis of an eating disorder prevents children from maturing in a healthy way. With this being said, eating disorders are also detrimental to the health of people past the age of puberty. Eating disorders frequently prohibit those affected from getting the nutrients that they need to maintain good health.  Also related to this is the concept of diet culture. Diet culture is the societal belief that physical appearance is more important than physical and mental well-being. This concept was widely accepted by my peers by the time I entered middle school, and this culture enabled and continues to enable the development of eating disorders in young women.
Around the time I turned eighteen, I was diagnosed with bulimia. Growing up, I was always taller and lankier than my peers, and I always stuck out in a crowd. I was incredibly self-conscious about this, so as I got older and my body started to change, I wanted to do everything that I could in an attempt to fit society’s ideal beauty standard. Being tall is typically considered to be unfeminine, and because I was very involved as a competitive swimmer, I was also muscular with broad shoulders, adding to my masculine traits. Many of my friends, and lots of girls my age regularly made fun of me for this, causing me to do everything in my power to prove my femininity and fit the male gaze in other ways. Namely, I started experimenting with makeup, clothes, and weight loss. During this time, I was a healthy weight for my gender and age, but I found myself comparing my body type to the edited pictures of models in bikinis in the media, as well as my more petite peers. Because of this, I certainly felt the pressure to work to conform to society’s beauty standards. There were many factors that eventually led to my bulimia diagnosis, all centered around conforming to society’s beauty standards, and this is something that I still struggle with even today, despite knowing these expected standards of beauty are totally unrealistic. 
		In order to further understand this, it seems pertinent to examine the work of Namoi Wolf and the concept of the beauty myth. The beauty myth is essentially the standard of the physical appearance of women, and the idea that a woman’s value is determined based on whether or not she meets this standard. It is a sexist ideal that runs our society in an attempt to control women’s bodies and self-esteem. The phrase “it’s a man’s world” is incredibly relevant here, as women are subjected to the beauty myth because our culture is dominated by men’s power and institutions. This is seen in our daily lives, as the beauty myth is perpetuated by social media, advertisements, and other platforms that project unrealistic body expectations for women. The beauty myth is determined by politics and is designed to keep male dominance intact. Since men are trying to maintain dominance, women are forced into society’s standards in order to fight against each other for the resources that men have appropriated for themselves. Additionally, we see that as a woman’s social power increases, so does the beauty standard that she is expected to fulfill. Frequently, this pressure prevents women from reaching their full potential and being the most effective they can be. A different example of how the beauty myth is seen in our society is plastic surgery. The practice of plastic surgery has increased in relatively recent years, but specifically cosmetic surgery is primarily performed on women. Women who undergo breast augmentation, facial lifts, rhinoplasties, or a number of other procedures do so even when it is not medically necessary, but instead, fit society’s definition of beauty. This myth is a travesty in and of itself, but what makes it even worse is that there is no corollary myth for men. While it is true that men strive to have good looks, they simply do not face the same pressures women have to be attractive. Conclusively, the beauty myth is a belief system studied by Wolf that ensures male dominance stays intact in every aspect of society, but actively diminishes the worth of women by judging them solely off of appearance. 
	Overall, today’s widespread problem of eating disorders, particularly in young women and girls can be explained by the concept of the beauty myth. Because women are only valued in society if they are beautiful in the eyes of men, many women are pushed to attempt to achieve these unattainable standards in extremely unhealthy ways. The idea of the beauty myth is ingrained in the minds of women starting at a very young age, meaning that these unhealthy coping mechanisms frequently develop early, leaving girls with lifelong insecurities as well as worrying mental and psychical health conditions, like eating disorders. It is important to note that driving women to such lengths is simply a sadistic control method to keep men in positions of power and to ensure that women compete with each other instead of with men. It is despicable that this misogynistic belief rules our society, and that young women and girls are forced to suffer the consequences of male insecurity.

 Religion in a Post-Truth World

     People are born with an innate sense of right and wrong. Where does this come from? Are we born knowing not to steal, lie, and cheat, but do so anyway? Do we know not to hit other kids, or take their toys? What are we told and how do we feel when we do? Where do our ethical and moral choices come from? Harari discusses possible answers to these questions in his book, 21 Lessons for the 21st Century in the sections labeled, Secularism, God, Religion, and Post-Truth World. To discover the truth, we must first ask the question, what is truth? Is it simply something we know to be true? Is truth the same for all people? 
     Religion is not something uncommon, or new. It can be seen throughout all corners of the earth, through all different languages, cultures, and societies. Religion is so important, that there are hundreds upon hundreds of differing beliefs, gods, spiritualities, and more. “Religion is a universally and uniquely human phenomenon in that all human societies possess recognizably religious beliefs and practices, but (as far as we can tell) only human societies do so. Together, these observations suggest that religion is closely related to human nature, and perhaps explicable as a function thereof. At the same time, the indubitably social enactment and implications of religion, as well as the socially determined nature of its contents, ensure that any meaningful attempt to explain religion must simultaneously be a sociological exercise.” (Marshall, 2016)   
   There are many different ways to define “truth.” There is a spiritual or meditative sense of truth, and then there is personal truth. Lastly there is just truth, in the sense that it aligns with given facts or reality, such as “The sky is blue.” “Of course the cosmic mystery doesn’t help us at all in maintaining the social order. People often argue that we must believe in a god that gave some very concrete laws to humans, or else morality will disappear and society will collapse into primeval chaos.” (Harari, 2018) 
     Earlier this semester in this class, there were readings and discussions of the Matrix of Domination and Power in America. Both of these can correlate to the previously mentioned sections of Harari’s book by looking at how religion was used to enforce these beliefs and ideas. Harari believes that Religion or God is not actually about “god” but about humans and that religion is all about stories that give legitimacy and validation to a previously established authority. Also correlating to the collective consciousness, people take this idea of religion and use it to control or have authority over an enormous mass of people. 
      Other important topics by Harari that come into play when discussing these topics are the  ideas of “Truth” and living in a “Post-Truth” world, as well as how that affects how people live their lives ethically and morally today. Without a higher authority, or set of given rules and beliefs to follow, how does society and its people function? We are currently living in a world where truth is more and more often seen as being relative. “What’s true for me is not necessarily true for you.” I have my beliefs, you have yours, and that’s that. 
      Is it possible that these collective beliefs and ideas can be harming us? Are they dangerous to this new generation that questions and defies everything because of the media that is presented to them? Why is the truth so important? At first, that may sound like a dumb question. But every day, more and more, little by little, the truth is changing. Government officials lie, companies lie about what's in their food and products, even teachers lie about the subject matter of their choice. Along with the rise of technology and therefore, science, the “truth” is changing more and more. Everything I was raised to believe as “True” has now been challenged, and things that I was told were “lies” are now making much more sense than what I was originally taught to believe growing up. 
     In contrast to Harari, Emile Durkheim believed that the societal formation of the collective consciousness furnishes us with both stability and truth.  Because the collective consciousness is not artificial, made by an unspoken agreement of a multitude of groups of people, it is deemed trustworthy. It is embraced because of the fear of being left out, or different, or alone. It is only aware of what it needs to establish authority. Additionally, religion is used as a sort of resource to give meaning or purpose to life.
    Another large matter when it comes to the importance of religion and truth, is “meaning” or “purpose.” Durkheim's theory of religion is approached from the perspective of his lifelong concern with the question of meaning and moral order in modern society. Really thinking about the reason people exist, and why and how life, community, and the world works scientifically and down to the design of a hummingbird or toucan, or life cycle of a butterfly is extremely important to think about. 
      For Durkheim, the religion of society was important to study because he believed that religion provided social cohesion to help maintain social solidarity through shared rituals and beliefs, social control to enforce religious based morals, and an atmosphere to help maintain conformity and control in society. It has become increasingly likely that religion nowadays is used as a fear tactic to scare people and control them and their actions. For example, “You don’t believe in God? You’re not a christian? Aren’t you scared of hell?” And rather than basing any of their beliefs in fact and/or truth, they use fear and threats to get the collective consciousness to obey their “God given rules.” 
      To sum up, truth is astronomically important, but we can not use religion as a basis of truth as a force to control others. While Durkheim and Harari both make good points, neither have any one perfect answer to the various questions that are so important. With today's constant and ever-changing technology, media, and ideas and beliefs, truth is something to both be consistently challenged, and researched.

	Throughout time over the past few decades society has evolved and constantly changed the definition of what it means to “do gender”, it has become new meanings on what a person needs to do to play the role of your assigned gender just to fit into societies standards, and to be viewed as normal. This has become new standards for women such as how they dress, how they have to act, especially when it comes to a man, and as well as their career path. For men, it has become an image of mainly how they have to act, and especially how they treat women. This normalization of what you should be doing to “do gender” ultimately has a negative impact on everyone’s lives. 

	I attended a private school for most of my life, so while I was there I witnessed a lot of examples of “doing gender”. It raised me to believe that these expectations that society has to fit into its standards of how each gender is supposed to play their role were normal. It taught me that if I were to show any emotion it would be seen by people as me being weak and that I would lose my sense as a man. Everyone that I was around all the time in school fit into these roles as well. All of the girls would wear the typical clothing society portrays, such as the short shorts, skirts, tank tops, leggings, and if a girl tried to wear any clothing that would classify them as a “tomboy”, they would instantly be judged by everyone else in the community.

 
	On the other hand all of the guys in my school including myself because of how we were raised, and the community we were in based on the school, kind of fit into the typical toxic masculinity role. Ever since the start, we were extremely competitive in everything we did, and even things that were nowhere near a competition, we turned it into one. No matter what was going on in our lives, you would never see any of us show any sort of emotion or sadness, because we did not want to get made fun of, or looked at as weak by all of the other guys. 

	On top of making things a competition, the atmosphere was extremely hostile towards one another at all times. Although most of us were friends, there was a constant argument and people making fun of other people just to bring them down, to make themselves seem more powerful and superior. It usually tended to work too, because the louder the guy was the fewer guys would talk back to him. 

	The question to this whole gender role stigma that both genders tend to face, is why this ideology is still practiced and upheld in society. Over time we have broken some of the typical traditions that both genders uphold especially when it comes to females. This goes back to the main three different waves of feminism which have completely changed the outlook on how women are supposed to act in society. 

	First wave feminism goes back to starting all the way in the 1870s when women were pushing to change the way America’s voting system worked where women were able to vote. This was important to breaking the chains of sexism and blindly following the idea of “doing gender”. Women began to realize that they can fight to become more of an equal presence in society, and hold more power. Instead of being seen as others, women fought to show that they are human too and it is not just the man who has power, and has an important role in society. 

	After the first wave of feminism, the second wave of feminism began shortly after World War II. Women became tired of not being seen as equals in the workforce, where men could only do the heavy work, and women tended to be stuck being a housewife and care for the husband and family, or do jobs that were seen as “less important in society”. They were able to fight once again and show that they are just as capable of playing an important role in the world, and it is not just men that have the control. 

	Finally, we have the third wave feminism which is still currently an issue, or also known as the sexual revolution. This allowed for a lot more inclusivity for women and to be able to live their lives and express themselves more freely. The consequence of this that I believe can be seen today, is the over-sexualization of women from men as well as in the marketing strategies. Women are now constantly having to deal with issues of catcalling and being seen as objects as well as subjects to sexual harassment. The marketing strategies do not help with this ideology and problem that society faces because they try to use women and the idea of sex appeal to help sell their idea and project. 

This is all part of the idea of “doing gender”, because both genders fall into this role. Women are raised to believe that they are seen as objects and subjects to men, as bad as it sounds. And men are raised to believe that women are just simply objects and trophies to be shown off and obtained for self-gain and power by men. Now of course not all of society is raised to believe and think this way, but it tends to be the normal idea in smaller more private parts of the world, especially small towns in the south. This is because they keep the idea of how doing gender was seen a long time ago, and that idea just repeats itself over and over throughout generations.

This is also shown by the writing done by de Beauvoir, of how women are seen as lesser to men and viewed instead as an “other”. She goes on to discuss how men will never bring up their gender or start off something by describing how “I am a man”. She goes on to discuss how no one ever questions the ideology or beliefs a man has, simply because he is a man. But for women, she says from personal experience that women will get judged on their beliefs and told they are incorrect as she says, “You only think that because you’re a woman.”  This goes to show the daily life and struggle especially as a woman to play this idea of gender roles and to do gender, especially when in society women have always been viewed and treated as inferior. 

The examples of the three waves of feminism are important because it shows that society is capable of breaking ideas of doing gender, and how the two genders have to play their role in society. But it also shows that so far we have been incapable of being able to break this never-ending cycle of there always being some sort of standards in society that the genders have to uphold to be seen as normal. 


What I believe can be learned from this analysis is that society needs to break this cycle that it has created of doing gender, and eliminate our idea as a whole of how we believe a certain gender should act or display themselves. Even the waves of feminism help back this up as well as statistics of mental health disorders and suicide rates of men. This chain will not be broken until both women and men can act how they would like and be viewed by society as equals, where both can have power and influence. As well as men developing the idea of it being okay to show weakness and show their emotion instead of society making them feel like they have to play the power-hungry role as well as the alpha dog role. Society would be better as a whole if we could break the cycle of “doing gender” and change the meaning behind it because ultimately it does more harm in the world than it does good.

In western cultures, hegemonic masculinity is highly valued. This is the classic idea of what a man should be. Hegemonic masculinity refers to a man being physically and mentally strong, providing, wealthy, and emotionless or grounded. This idea of the perfect western man has shaped the way men act in their everyday lives. Men in the western world hold the positions of power, make the most money, but are still often unhappy. Men also lead the statistics in suicide rates and cheating within long-term relationships and marriages. A newer trend shows that young men are having less sex than ever. Are these signs of truly strong people? Many problems that affect men specifically, would be greatly improved by men adopting feminine qualities and behaviors. 
	In an attempt to deal with these societal problems, right- leaning parties have advocated for men to become more masculine in order to fight the issues. Masculinity and femininity can be measured on a spectrum. Trying to force men to act more masculine is no more than putting on a facade. This only leads to a further lack of authenticity of character in men, making matters worse.
	Boys in the western world are taught to act masculine very early on in childhood. Young males are pushed in the directions of interests such as toy cars, guns, and other manly activities. It would be very interesting to see how something as simple as toy selection would be different if all outside factors were taken out. For example, I grew up with a sister, and toy dolls were just as interesting to me as the toys made for boys. Furthermore, many extracurricular activities that kids engage in are split up by gender. Scouts organizations, sports, and even play groups are often split up by the sexes. We do not see many young boys being signed up for dance classes, yet many men wonder why they feel awkward on a dance floor in their adult lives. In schools, there are awkward dynamics between the sexes. I have memories of fears such as the “cooties” early in school, which embedded in kids to not associate with the other sex. Kids in the western world are conditioned early on to stick to their gender role in society.
	By the time boys reach adolescence, they view the opposite sex as the “other”. Looking back at my highschool experience, many boys including myself found it very difficult to talk to girls, even when there was no romantic interest. We were indirectly conditioned to view women as the “other”, not just people. Many kids have friend groups of one sex. In the case of adolescent boys, they often have superficial relationships with their best friends. It is not uncommon for friend groups of guys to not know major parts of one another’s lives. For example, one of my closest friends did not inform me of his mother having a serious health incident, for weeks. Even when he informed me of the news, it was talked about very briefly and casually. It seems men have difficulty in expressing emotions and feelings with each other. On the contrary, many friend groups of girls know everything about each other. As there is sometimes an issue with this, overall, men would greatly benefit from having deeper friendships with people because they would be able to offer the proper emotional support for one another when times get hard.
For a very long time in western society, men’s strongest relationships are with their spouse. Our society tells us that men are meant to save the intimacy and emotional talks for their wives or girlfriends. When have you seen a man crying on his friend's shoulder, aside from someone dying? This can often create unbalanced relationship dynamics, because women often have close friends to share emotions with outside of the romantic relationship. It seems it is very common for moms to have friend groups, but not dads. If I examine my parents’ social lives, my mom has far more friends than my dad. Furthermore, the friends my dad has are either from work, family, or through my mom’s friends. This can create an imbalance in a relationship or marriage because the woman often has more emotional outlets to vent to. Men’s social lives would be greatly improved if they had more platonic friends to spend time with and share emotions with. 
If we examine the dynamics of men’s romantic relationships in today’s landscape, things have become even worse. In addition to men lacking platonic supportive friendships, young men are failing to establish and maintain romantic sexual relationships. According to The Washington Post, the amount of men under 30 years old who have reported no sex in the last year, has skyrocketed to nearly 30% (Ingraham). Because people meet online more than in person these days, this trend can possibly be blamed on the dynamics of online dating applications. Apps like Tinder reward people based on the “matches” they get based on purely looks. Unfortunately, it has been theorized that a small percentage of the men on these applications receive the vast majority of all “matches”. This not only leaves men feeling defeated, but it also reinforces hegemonic masculinity by rewarding the good-looking strong men. If men are struggling to establish romantic relationships , and their platonic friendships are often superficial, how can they properly meet their emotional needs?
The final piece of the puzzle in the unhappy man is the way men work for a living. In our western society, men are expected to be the breadwinners for the family. This inevitably leads to men entering tough professions that they may not enjoy. Allocating the majority of one’s time to something they do not enjoy and receive fulfillment from is a recipe for disaster. When this is paired with lacking relationships, the potential for happiness is greatly reduced. Why is it that women are expected to stay home with the kids, yet many of them would like to pursue a career? The gender roles of society put people in lifestyles that are not suited for the individual. Men would be happier if they engaged in projects they truly cared for, with people they want to work with. In recent news, MMA fighter Jon Jones got arrested for domestic violence and damaging a police vehicle. Jones supposedly does what he loves for a living, but is clearly mentally ill and has an unbalanced life. He is the pinnacle of masculinity as he is strong, large, rich, and can literally end almost anyone's life with his hands. However, he is clearly a very unhappy and unsuccessful man. Happy successful people are in touch with their emotions, have a great support system, and engage in activities they truly enjoy.  Toxic masculinity standards do not strengthen people, it puts them in shackles from reaching their own destiny.
As stated earlier, the early years of a kid's life is very important in how the gender roles are enforced subconsciously. In order for boys in society to adopt more healthy feminine behaviors, it will be beneficial to teach these early on. The example of gendered toys was used earlier, but the issue is much deeper rooted. We must teach young boys the importance of building emotional management skills. Boys need to know that it is healthy to express emotions, even if this means crying or “appearing weak”. It will also benefit children when they are taught to socialize with the other sex. Splitting up the sexes does more harm than good as it creates strange dynamics early on that are hard to break.
Next, we must teach children the importance and skills of building friendships. We learn how to treat others with respect as kids, but it rarely goes much deeper than this. Young boys must learn how to share emotions with friends and family, instead of being taught to toughen up, which just teaches people to keep emotions bottled up. This extra education would hopefully lead to male students building meaningful relationships with peers, where they can freely share their emotions.
These healthy relationships must carry into adolescence and adulthood for men. When school, careers, and social aspects get harder as we get older, the relationships become more important than ever. Healthy platonic relationships lead to healthier and happier men, who are more effective in society.
Finally, men must engage in activities and possibly careers that are mentally fulfilling to them. In a perfect world, finance and gender roles will have minimal influence on the decision someone makes. However, more realistically we can hope that men pick careers that are sustainable mentally. We want to shift the paradigm away from teaching men that they must run themselves into the ground in order to provide for the family. People must engage in more healthy lifestyles with balance, in order to be socially productive in society.
In conclusion, toxic masculinity creates many issues for men and the people around them in society. As many believe this is due to men being weak or too feminine, more femininity may actually be the key. Gender role conditioning begins at  a very young age, so if we focus less on these roles, and more on mental/emotional health and social skills, we will raise more socially efficient people. Also, it will be beneficial to let kids explore interests they actually enjoy and are drawn too, rather than grouping activities by the sexes. This way, kids can try multiple things and get new perspectives on who they truly are. Moving into adolescence and adulthood, men must continue to build social and emotional skills. Many men struggle to share emotions and keep things bottled up until it is too late. Women seem to socialize and support one another far more often, so men should follow their lead. Finally, we must inspire men by getting them to see the value of doing things that are fulfilling to them as individuals. This will shift some stress away from men, leading to a happier overall society.

Comparing Harari’s Views to Sociological Study
	In Harari’s “21 Lessons for the 21st Century,” he shares his views on the many controversial problems of the global society. Harari shares personal viewpoints and experiences, historical references, and social science to deeply explain where he stands. Harari’s text provides an updated view of sociology, compared to the most popular dated sociologists. This essay will highlight and explore contradictions between Harari and Durkheim on the topic of religion in a society and moral compasses. Next, the essay will dive into the many similarities between Harari and Mantsios regarding their views on hierarchal structures in societies and equality. 
In Durkheim’s “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations,” he argues that religions were important in creating the many ways that a society functions. Durkheim credits religion with developing the peak of societal function. Durkheim stated, “In fact, we have seen that if collective life awakens religious thought on reaching a certain degree of intensity, it is because it brings about a state of effervescence which changes the conditions of psychic activity” (Durkheim 73). Durkheim describes the vast power religion has in conjunction with the intensity of socialization and group thought. Durkheim goes on to explain morals and human thought, “Hence the individual at least obscurely takes account of the fact that above his private ideas, there is a world of absolute ideas according to which he must shape his own; he catches a glimpse of a whole intellectual kingdom in which he participates, but which is greater than he.” Durkheim believed that religions provide people with the collective consciousness of “truth”. The individual has the power to interpret the truth, but they can’t truly choose and decide what the truth is. Durkheim credits religion heavily for being the moral compass of people, guiding individuals in their beliefs of what is wrong or right in any situation. 
Harari has a far different take on how religion functions in a society, and how individuals form a moral compass. Harari explains, “﻿There are no “Muslim” or “Jewish” positions here. Humankind is likely to be divided into two main camps—those in favor of giving AI significant authority, and those opposed to it. 	It is not often that a person has the chance to experience and observe the workings of white privilege from both sides of the equation. Growing up in an interracial family has opened my eyes to exactly how my fair skin benefits me in life, and how my siblings’ dark skin disadvantages theirs. White privilege is often not realized or willingly acknowledged by many people of the Caucasian race. As Peggy McIntosh states in White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack, “White privilege is like an invisible weightless knapsack of special provisions, maps, passports, codebooks, visas, clothes, tools and blank checks.” (30) I never fully comprehended the amount of advantages I had growing up in the dominantly white United States until the adoption of my siblings, who are both from Ethiopia, Africa, and are currently middle and high school age. Hearing the experiences and concerns of my siblings opened my eyes to the following: white privilege does indeed have a concrete existence in our everyday lives, created through the systemic racism present in American society, and our unwillingness to recognize such privilege only fuels that system further. 
	A distinct memory I have from when I was around eight or nine years old is constantly being praised for adopting my brother and sister. When sharing that I have two adopted siblings to someone new, I was often told something along the lines of, “That is so great of your family!” or, “I bet they are so thankful for what you’ve done for them.” Even from such a young age, I always found the comment strange. In recent years I realized it was because it is coming from a privileged and “white savior” perspective, whereas I never saw their adoption through that lens. The adults who praised me most likely did so because, in their eyes, my siblings were lesser and needed our saving. White it is true that they came from a poor country with less opportunity, there are many people living in Ethiopia under the same circumstances who have never known any different. My parents did not adopt with the intentions of being praised or receiving thanks, but rather felt that their faith called them to expand our family through the adoption process. This viewpoint was the beginning of my realization of how much privilege white people receive in our country, to the extent that we place ourselves on a pedestal for opening our homes to those of a different race. 
	Another example of this privilege is that I’ve never realized that I have been surrounded by people of my race for my entire life. My parents sent me and each of my siblings to private school for most of our education, and I never realized that there virtually no students of color in the school until my brother or sister would mention it. The school setting made them feel different and outside of the normal, whereas I never gave it a second thought because almost every other peer looked like me. I recall my sister being sad because the only other black girl in her grade was not playing basketball, so she was the only person of color on the team. Nearly all of my siblings’ friends are white as well, taking away that shared experience of being the same race that can create a special connection. While it is of course a good thing to have a diverse friend group, I have never had the issue of not having any friends of the same race as me, something that I would surely miss if that was the case. I have always had the privilege of being within the dominant racial group in the United States, making it easy for me to be surrounded people who are also white. We are taught from a young age that, in our society, skin color has meaning and is a means of interconnection between people of a like race. Whereas I have always had access to that connection, my siblings have not, and therefore feel isolated and abnormal at times because of it. 
	The final example is one many people of all races have finally begun to pay attention to, and that is the often unfair treatment of black people by law enforcement and other authorities in the United States. My parents have had to initiate talks with my brother and sister about exactly how to behave when within the same area as law enforcement, especially when driving. Sentences such as “Never move your hands from the wheel,” and, “Announce every action you are about to perform, so they don’t think you are trying to run or pull out a weapon,” have been told to both siblings many times. My sister just obtained her driver’s license very recently, and once again had to be given the same talk. It might seem tedious and dramatic to some, but it is a real fear for black people every day. This fear is something I have never had to experience or be warned about. These fears carry over into other aspects of my siblings’ everyday life. My brother must be told not to act foolish with his white friends, even if they are behaving that way, in case he gets singled out by a person of authority, such as a police officer, or even a teacher. As he gets older, he is not supposed to walk or ride his bike around our predominantly white neighborhood alone, for fear of having someone call the police for trespassing despite our family living there for over seven years. I get in the car to drive, or take my dogs for a walk, without a second thought of how the color of my skin could put me in a position of danger. This is yet another example of the seemingly invisible privilege white people have simply due to their race. 
	How do we know that this is white privilege and not just a handful of random experiences? Peggy McIntosh better explores these advantages in her previously mentioned text, White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack. In her writing, she provides a self-made checklist of assumptions and benefits she feels she inherently receives a right to because of her whiteness. This checklist was made based off of observing what freedoms and things assumed to happen in everyday life that McIntosh’s African American women coworkers did not have access to. 
	Many of these checklist points correlate to the paralleled experiences between me and my siblings, showing that their experiences and my advantages are not just random or individual. For example, my brother and sister feeling alienated at school corresponds with the privilege McIntosh describes when stating, “I can go home from most meetings of organizations I belong to feeling somewhat tied in, rather than isolated, out of place, outnumbered, unheard, held at a distance, or feared.” (33) I have always had the comfort of being surrounded by people of the same race as me in nearly all settings of my life, whereas my siblings do not often have that assurance. 
	Several other points on Mcintosh’s list also coincide almost directly with the extra obstacles put in place for my siblings because of their dark skin. These inherent advantages are “I can be pretty sure that my neighbors in a new location will be neutral or pleasant to me the day I move in,” (31) and, “If a traffic cop pulls me over […] I can be sure I haven’t been singled out because of my race.” (33) As previously mentioned, my siblings have to take extra precautions when performing simple tasks such as driving or walking in our neighborhood, just to be seen as a nonthreat to certain people. While these advantages white people receive seem like they should be the normal standard for all (and often are assumed to be afforded to all by white people), this is actually not the case. 
	Mcintosh begins to expand on how United States systems of government attempt to keep these unearned privileges hidden from white people, as a means to keep them blissfully ignorant in order to continue to support and stand by white-controlled institutions through “conferred dominance.” (34) This gives whites power over other racial groups due to unequal distribution of wealth and assets. Because this realization of the privileges white people receive has been kept from those of the Caucasian race for so long, accepting that such advantages exist becomes a difficult concept to grasp. 
	There are many white people, such as my grandparents, who have grown up in poor communities with little opportunity. To get out of the situation they were born into, many have had to work hard for what they have in life, following the classic “American dream” and “bootstraps mentality.” Because of this, white people in such a position often deny having such privilege, because they assume privilege only comes from a place of wealth and material possession when, in reality, they were already at an advantage to pull themselves out of poverty because of the color of their skin.
	McIntosh also describes a feeling similar to what I experienced when first discovering my inherent privilege, that makes the concept even harder to grasp. Growing up in America, we are taught that we live in a democratic society that provides equal opportunity for all, despite religion, race, age, and many other attributes. With the full acknowledgement of white privilege, Mcintosh states the all too familiar feeling of discovering the hidden truth, saying, “If these things were true, this was not such a free country; my life was not what I had made it; many doors opened for my people through no virtues of our own.” (33) This is what can make the acceptance of the existence of white privilege so daunting, because citizens of the United States are told one streamlined version of history, often leaving out the ugly truths and systemic inequalities that led to the creation of the nation. While people of color realize these inequalities from a young age, white people have often never had to reflect on them because we have no prior experience or knowledge of the inconsistencies within our society. 
	Without listening to and observing the experiences of my siblings, as well as the behavior and opinions directed towards my brother and sister by white people, I would have most likely remained blissfully ignorant of the privileges I have access to in my everyday life due to my skin color. This is why it becomes extremely important for white people to willingly listen and acknowledge the experiences of people of color in our countries, because it can be a vital way to understand and recognize the privileges we as white people inherently receive in our systemically racist society. However, McIntosh relays one important message in her writing: “Disapproving of these systems won’t be enough to change them.” (35) The first step to redesigning the systems of American society that put white people at an advantage is to accept that such systems and advantages exist in the first place. 
	In conclusion, the existence of white privilege in the United States is not just an opinion, but rather a tangible concept. This privilege provides white people with advantages, as well as access to basic rights and freedoms, that people of color in the nation are not awarded. Recognizing these privileges can be difficult, because American society attempts to keep white people unaware and denying of such advantages in order to maintain white dominance over other racial groups. Through the simple act of paying attention and being inclined to listen to those who are oppressed by white privilege, it can become quite clear that it does indeed exist. Acceptance of this concept is the first step in attempting to redefine the racially discriminatory systems white privilege was built within.

The Conception of Self
When a professor asks a question in class and one feels confident enough to think “I know this, I can answer this 100%” what is the determining factor in whether that person raises their hand to answer the professor’s question in front of the whole class? That factor in which we as humans always seem to lose faith in ourselves in fear of somehow getting the question that you know is correct wrong is called the Conception of Self. The first reading I am going to use is George Herbert Mead’s “The Self, The I, and the Me”. In the reading it becomes three different concepts; the “I” is the part of our brains that responds to stimuli being presented to us from the environment (like the example used previously) knowing the answer to a question when asked. The “Me” is the part of our brains that evaluates what this stimulus is and how it will be affecting us, the “What if it’s wrong, don’t raise your hand”. The “Self” is the part of our brains that exerts the emotions from the conversation between the “I” and the “Me” part of our brains. The self in the classroom situation would be feeling unconfident/nervous to answer the question due to the argument between the “I” and “Me”.
Now take the “I”, “Me”, and “Self” and consider Erving Goffman’s “The Presentation of Self”. In Goffman’s “The Presentation of Self” we see that the performance of the “I”, “Me” and “Self” depends on the type of interaction we are having. The literal presentation of one’s self solely depends on the audience. For example, my thought process for driving to school and my thought process driving home from school are two totally different fields. 
Those two concepts are responsible for the way we create a standard for ourselves in different settings. By using the Conception of Self-concept, we as humans have created a safety net for our own thoughts and actions. When we are with our families, we are going to act a lot different than we would if we were with friends, or if we were in the presence of our teachers or our employers, our brains have created different “modes” based on the constant internalized conversation we have with ourselves every second of every day when we make decisions.

What Part of The Me Do Serial Killers Lack?
A question that remains unanswered when criminal cases involve scenes of serial killers is why? Why do serial killers feel the need to act on their urges? What part of the personality has so much control that causes the concluding actions of a desire to end in the form of a life being taken? There are three parts to the personality that impact who we are and who we become. First, the social self pertains to the recognition we receive from others (how they see us in their minds). Second, the material self, which by all means is the one part of ourselves that changes least, is responsible for the things we claim and disclaim that all impact who we become. Lastly, the ego, which is responsible for how we see ourselves and is also subject to change the most. A significant driving force impacted by all three of these personality contributions is either a hyperactive nature and nurture influence during early childhood development or the total absence of a nature and nurture influence altogether. Serial killers are motivated by a strong force from the version of “me" that could be dangerous when not controlled. While all parts of the "self" play a role in outward behavior and interaction with others, the version of the self that thrives on stability is the ego. When the ego becomes uncontrollable, so does the individual. 
In William James' The Self and Its Selves, the concept of self is analyzed. James claims that "In its widest possible sense, however, a man's self is the sum total of all that he CAN call his, not only his body and his psychic powers, but his clothes and his house, his wife and children, his ancestors and friends, his reputation and words, his lands and horses, and yacht and bank-account. All of these things give him the same emotion" (James, 122). In other words, every aspect of our lives plays a role in who we are as people. The daily interactions we unknowingly participate in have an impact on who we are; the slightest bit of change in tone during a conversation can have an unnoticed effect on our subconscious. When the things around us thrive and flourish, so do we. When the things around us crash and burn, so do we, in a way. Who we are can be respectively divided into four categories/sections belonging to two separate groups. The most active part of our personality is responsible for all of our interactions. 	
The part of who we are that strictly relies on others to function and is the easily most affected version of ourselves impacted by others, the Social Self. According to William James, the social self is the part of us that seeks validation from others, "A man's Social Self is the recognition which he gets from his mates" (James, 123). Social interactions play a vital role in the development of our brains and our emotions. When we are exposed to others at a young age, our brains start to register the "role" or "front" is used to interact with another person as the Social Self, "in very early childhood, new procedural memories for interacting with others and for regulating effects can be formed more easily than they can ever be again" (Tyson, Journal of the American Psychoanalytic Association).  The lack of healthy interaction at such a young age suggests that children have a reduced development of their sense of agency, their ability to establish moral standards, their ability to assume self-responsibility, and have no capacity for emotional regulation. Many serial killers are victims of rejection at some point in their life. Due to the lack of interaction in early childhood, the rejection is more of a devastation than a simple awkward interaction, "it may seem to be counterintuitive on the surface, but many serial killers are actually insecure individuals who are compelled to kill due to a morbid fear of rejection. In many cases, the fear of rejection seems to result from having been abandoned by their mother in early childhood' (Bonn, Understanding What Drives Serial Killers). James refers to the lack of interaction or being "unnoticed by all members thereof" as the most "fiendish punishment that could be devised." Receiving validation from others is essential in developing our ability to understand and return self-expression to others. 
            The material self can pertain to the body, "the innermost part of the material self in each of us…" (James, 123). The things we own, such as clothes, also fit into this category because we use clothes to identify and showcase who we are to the outside world. In other words, we express ourselves through the things we call our own. Family applies to this category; the people who raise us, whether it is immediate family or not, become a part of who we are due to their influence on us as children. The role of the family in one's life is critically impacted when it comes to nature vs. nurture. When children are raised on love and affection, their outlook tends to be more positive and joyful. The opposite is in order for when children are raised on hatred and fear; their perspective tends to be more hostile and aggressive. During the infant stage, the sight of aggression in young children is expected due to the lack of self-expression available in their minds. This lack of self-expression results in few ways to attain attention to the issue the infant needs attention for, "both healthy and pathological aggression involve the intent to harm (in reality or fantasy) and tend to become accompanied with by unpleasant effects such as anger fear or frustration." (Fonagy, Aggression and the Psychological Self) From a young age, the lack of love and the integration of aggression leads to the exposure of violence due to the lack of self-expression available in the infant mind, he or she who is exposed to the hatred at such a young age will only grow and develop their own aversion to the ones who appeared to him/her, "They may come to believe that by destroying the person he desires prior to entering into a relationship with them, he can eliminate the frightening possibility of being abandoned, humiliated or otherwise hurt by someone he loves, as he was in childhood" (Bonn, Understanding What Drives Serial Killers). Until self-expression can be controlled, violence will continue to be a result of aggression, and it will only become a more driving force in the lives of those affected. 
As humans continue to develop, the piece responsible for how a person feels about themselves does too. The part of the mind accountable for a person's sense of self-esteem or self-importance, "the ego is the component of personality that is responsible for dealing with reality" (Cherry, Id, Ego, and Superego Are Part of a Structural Model of Personality). Beginning in the early stages of development, through praise, verbal/nonverbal affirmations, and positive influences, the ego is created for a healthy mental state and positive self-esteem.  These experiences are essential during the early stages of development because it healthily encourages self-love and appreciation. On the other hand, when there is a lack of affirmations and praises, it can have an even more significant impact than receiving the assurances. When children are exposed to feelings such as anger at such a young age, their physical development is impaired, "In these formulations, aggression is an annihilating presence in the infant. It is an anti-life, anti-self-force; an impediment to the development of the ego, rather than the ego's protest at the presence of impediments in the environment." (Fonagy, Aggression and the Psychological Self). In cases where aggression is all a child knows, there is no comprehensible version of positive emotions in their minds. When all the child knows is anger and fear, these emotions gaining strength from being present at a young age can result in the "wrong idea" about life in general; this “wrong idea” from childhood results in a bitter and hateful individual. The child that was raised on hatred only grows in rage as they age. 
The concept in question is why serial killers are the way are they are. The answer to this question may seem complex, but I believe it is simple. Instead of the argument being nature vs. nurture, the concept being challenged should be either too much or not enough nature and nurture will result in a corrupt person, "It is futile to try to separate developmental influences on children into nature and nurture," says George Holden, chair of the department of psychology at Southern Methodist University. The "nature" part of child development refers to the individual's genetic make-up regarding development and learning. In other words, our nature is how we are predestined to develop and grow up. An example of how nature is responsible is when someone becomes a suspect for murder- a serial killer, their relatives and friends say, "that's not in his nature," referring to the fact that it could not possibly be the person they knew because "they are not capable" of that form of evil. Another example can be seen in the bible, "the sin nature manifested itself early in the genealogy: the very first child born to Adam and Eve, Cain, became the very first murderer" (Genisis 4:8). The concept of "nurture" is the general influence external pressures having on an individual, these influences ranging from family and upbringings to education. However, it has been proven that our genetic predisposition only has a growing impact on how we act. If children grow up in an entirely different environment from their parents, they are more likely to have a more substantial nurture impact. Theodore Wachs, a psychologist at Purdue University who studies child development, quoted, "if only because the environmental context, broadly conceived, that kids grow up in may be quite different from the environmental context their parents grew up in." Too much nature and nurture in a person can lead to dangerous outcomes. Not enough nature and nurture can lead to far more hazardous results; therefore, children must grow and develop a personality on their own terms. 
The lack of social interaction that is now in effect because of the pandemic we are in is responsible for the growing aggression throughout the world. With this “new way of life” that is now being traditionalized in many homes, “seriously, given the severity of the coronavirus and how it is impacting us in the form of fear and inconvenience, those things that bothered us before the outbreak that began in Wuhan, China, in December—not even three months ago—don’t seem so bad after all. Coronavirus has put a lot into perspective” (Hyken, The Good Old Days). COVID-19 has removed a large number of components responsible for healthy development. Children born in this pandemic and children in their most prime developmental stage have all been deprived of at least one crucial part of the “me.”  Without a solid contribution from each of the categories, social, material, and ego, children are likely to grow up with a heightened sense of aggression and a deficit of understanding right and wrong. 
Serial killers and ordinary people all share the same components and concepts of the "Me." Each person, no matter their morals, has a social, material, and egotistical self. The differing factor comes into play during the early stages of life. In life, if the "normal" individual, love and affection are shown and implemented throughout the span of most their entire life. Beginning in early childhood up to when those responsible for the love and respect no longer exist, these individuals are shown positive reinforcement. Those who are raised on aggression and hatred follow a very different path of life. When all this individual is able to process is hatred and aggression, their ability to express compassion and love has now been rerouted to resulting in violence to express their desires. While the component of self is consistent from person to person, the development of these components in each individual varies extensively. Each variation of these features comes with its own identity; as James William would say, "the personal identity would not exist as a fact: but it would exist as a feeling all the same." Personal identity is not just the identity of the person; it is the environment around the person; it is their family or lack thereof, it is their interactions at a young age, it is the emotions they were exposed to as children. The material is self is what we are made of. The social self is who others say we are, and the ego self is who we say we are. When these three components are aligned, the future seems bright, but there is no way to predict the damage when these three components are not aligned.

Commodity Fetishism vs. McDonaldization
In sociology, two known concepts, commodity fetishism and McDonaldization, offer interesting perspectives on modern society.  While both ideas deal with characteristics of modern capitalism and its impact on society, they do so from different perspectives, focusing opposite tendencies in the trade of things and the rationalization of social processes. A comparison review of these ideas and a real-world scenario allows us to better comprehend their consequences and judge how effective they are in explaining current events.
Commodity Fetishism: According to Karl Marx's ideas, commodity fetishism is the social trends in which goods have meaning in addition to their physical worth. Goods carry social meanings and wants in capitalist countries in addition to being useful items. This obsession hides the social context of production, making people mistakenly believe that goods possess magical qualities instead of being the result of labor produced by humans.. 
McDonaldization: George Ritzer, a sociologist, developed the term "McDonaldization" to refer to the process of simplifying and reducing procedures, especially in relation to fast-food restaurants such as McDonald's. It means using effective and controllable methods to a range of areas of life, including food service, healthcare, and education. McDonaldization is a symbol of the success of efficiency and reason over feeling in modern social structures.
Comparisons: While both ideas develop in the context of capitalism, they differ in their focus and level.  Commodity fetishism is concerned primarily with the meaning associated with things, emphasizing the creation of value in consumer society. In contrast, McDonaldization focuses on process simplification and standards, emphasizing experience equality and the development of efficiency-oriented systems.
Contrasts: One key distinction between the two concepts lies in their treatment of agency. Commodity fetishism underscores the agency of consumers in attributing value to commodities through their consumption choices and cultural practices. On the other hand, McDonaldization emphasizes the role of institutional structures in shaping social processes, often leading to the disenchantment and standardization of everyday life.
Real-World Scenario: Consider the rise of coffee culture in the 21st century.  Coffee, originally considered a simple beverage, has grown into a symbol of status, personality, and lifestyle for many people. The growth of specific coffee shops, each with their own blends, brewing processes, and atmosphere, shows commodity fetishism. Coffee is no longer viewed just as a caffeine source, but rather as an experience to be enjoyed, shared on social media, and connected with specific identities.
Simultaneously, the coffee sector has become McDonaldized, particularly with the rise of global coffee franchises such as Starbucks. These businesses simplify the coffee-drinking experience with the same menus, store layouts, and service processes around the world. Starbucks' efficiency-driven approach, which focuses on speed, consistency, and convenience, illustrates  simplified structure.
Despite its flaws, commodity fetishism and McDonaldization continue to be popular concepts for understanding modern society's complexities. Commodity fetishism raises questions about the social creation of value, as well as how consumer culture impacts identities and relationships. Recognizing the symbolic elements of goods allows us to better understand how people interact with their social environment through buying habits.
McDonaldization, focuses on reason and standard of social processes, highlighting the broad impact of things being simplified in modern organizations. While McDonaldization might ignore the wide range of human experiences, it provides important insights into the techniques used by modern capitalism to streamline our daily lives. By combining these viewpoints and analyzing with their effects, we could create deeper views of capitalism's difficult relationship with culture and social organization in the twenty-first century.
Both commodity fetishism and McDonaldization offer valuable insights into contemporary society, yet they have their limitations. Commodity fetishism effectively highlights the cultural and symbolic dimensions of consumption, shedding light on how commodities become repositories of social meaning. However, it may overlook structural inequalities in the production and distribution of goods, focusing primarily on consumer behaviors and cultural practices.
Similarly, McDonaldization provides a compelling framework for understanding the rationalization of modern institutions and the proliferation of efficiency-driven systems. Yet, it tends to oversimplify complex social phenomena, reducing them to calculable and predictable processes. Moreover, McDonaldization overlooks the diversity of human experiences and the potential for resistance against rationalized systems.
In conclusion, while commodity fetishism and McDonaldization offer valuable perspectives on the dynamics of modern capitalism, they should be viewed as complementary rather than competing theories. A nuanced understanding of contemporary society requires integrating insights from both concepts, recognizing the interplay between symbolic meanings and institutional structures in shaping social life. By critically evaluating these concepts and applying them to real-world scenarios, we can deepen our understanding of the complexities of consumer culture and societal organization in the 21st century.

The Erosion of the Human Experience: Estranged Labor and McDonaldization
	The innate nature of human beings has always been a prevalent topic discussed among sociologists for centuries with many focusing on the idea of how our environment itself may shape our relationships. Among these sociologists some believe that human beings are inherently social creatures with the capability of expressing cooperation and collective action, yet this is not something commonly seen within today's society. One man who researched this disconnect between our nature and our actions was Karl Marx with his famous writings on “estranged labor.” Much later in time another sociologist by the name of George Ritzer focused on a similar topic, named McDonaldization, which is more in tune with modern occurrences and examples. Although these separate ideas were built nearly a century apart, both McDonaldization and estranged labor come together in order to highlight the dehumanizing effects of capitalist production as well as the loss of autonomy that comes with it.
	According to Karl Marx, human beings are incredibly unique creatures due to their capacity to interact and produce labor both creatively and socially. He argues that this production of labor is exactly what helped individuals develop their identities and later shape society. However, Marx states that in capitalist societies, workers become disconnected from the products of their labor, from the process of labor itself, and from their own humanity. This separation is referred to as “estranged labor” or “alienated labor.” This estrangement occurs because workers do not have control over what they produce, how they produce it, or the conditions under which they work. Instead, they are often reduced to mere cogs in a machine, performing repetitive tasks without any sense of fulfillment or connection to their work. Overall, work under capitalism subverts Marx’s view on human nature because it alienates individuals from each other which enforces a rigid division of labor with the entire process undermining the intrinsic satisfaction of work and limits individual potential.
	Ritzer's idea of "McDonaldization" builds on Marx's concept of alienation but applies it specifically to the context of fast-food restaurants, particularly McDonald's. McDonaldization refers to the process by which principles of fast food, such as efficiency, calculability, predictability, and control are prioritized through automation. However, Ritzer also argues that these key aspects of McDonaldization are increasingly dominating various aspects of society beyond the realm of food service and beginning to seep into other foundations such as retail chains, education facilities, and even social media. This growing concept is referred to as rationalization which describes the transformation of social and economic life from traditional and value driven systems to those based on efficiency, calculation, and control. 	
The connection between Marx's concept of estranged labor and Ritzer's theory of McDonaldization is rooted in their shared emphasis on the dehumanizing consequences within the capitalist system of production and consumption. Both feature individuals, whether as workers or consumers, being stripped of their intrinsic humanity and reduced to mere components within a larger mechanized apparatus. Instead, they become mere instruments in the pursuit of profit, engaged in repetitive tasks that divorce them from any genuine connection to the products they create or the process of labor itself. Similarly, Ritzer's idea of McDonaldization extends this dehumanization to the realm of consumption, particularly within the fast-food industry but also across broader domains. The overall focus on efficiency underlines the systematic detraction of agency as well as the commodification of human existence.
In conclusion, while theories have varied, one consistent theme on the evolution of human nature is the tension between the potential for cooperation inherent in human beings and the realities of societal structures that often inhibit such tendencies. Karl Marx's concept of estranged labor sheds light on how capitalist modes of production alienate individuals from the fruits of their labor, leading to a loss of autonomy and a sense of disconnection from their work and fellow human beings. This notion, rooted in Marx's analysis of capitalism, resonates with George Ritzer's theory of McDonaldization, which highlights how the principles of efficiency and predictability in fast-food culture have permeated various aspects of contemporary society, further eroding human agency and individuality.

Title
	What constitutes the “self” within a person’s stream of consciousness has always been a debated topic among Sociologists for centuries. Some believe that the “self” is merely a way for the body to capture experiences and is merely constructed from two separate ideas. Others share the belief that the “self” is a part of something much greater and can be divided into several  different parts which each specialize in one of three categories. Among these sociologists are William James and George Herbert Mead who both spent much of their lives organizing their views on the topic and although they have a fair amount of differences, their ideas on the self are still quite comparable. This comparison can be shown through Mead’s concept of experience and Jame’s concept of the “social self.”
	George Herbert Mead is among the sociologists who define the self as working in balance with the body in a construct known as “mind-body duality.” This idea revolves around experiences and the way that an individual experience is interpreted and taken in by both the body and mind separately. An experience of the body is considered to be done directly because when the body is exposed to a stimulus it is able to directly capture the experience. An experience of the mind/self is considered to be done indirectly because when the self is exposed to a stimulus it is only able to experience it through the body, however, the self is able to reflect on the overall experience and think about it later. So although the body is able to feel things directly, the experience is incomplete and even though the mind is able to experience a stimulus completely, it is done indirectly through the body. This idea of the self displays Mead’s concept in how the self is merely an extension of the mind that helps us reflect on our outside environments in a more complete manner so that we can learn and grow from our experiences.
	William James believed that the self is such a complicated construct that it must be divided into three separate parts: the material self, the social self, and the spiritual self. His rationale for this idea is that a human being can have so many materialistic and interpersonal connections throughout their life that it becomes hard to distinguish themselves from what they own. In summary the material self refers to a person’s property and body, the social self refers to how they are perceived and accepted by others, and the spiritual self is their emotions and inner thoughts. Although the material self and emotional self are both essential parts of James’ overall construct, the social self is the most relevant in terms of comparison to Mead’s ideas. In general the social self can be seen best through the differing personalities one expresses based on the environment they are in or who they are currently around. For example if someone is with a trusted partner or friend they know intimately then they will tend to be a bit more vulnerable and open. However, if they are among strangers they may be less open and therefore perceived as standoffish and quiet. Both examples showcase instances of the social self as well as how it is easily influenced and changed based on a stimulus or environment.
	Although Mead’s and James’ opinions and explanations of the self differ greatly in definition and example I believe that their concepts are still comparable and coexist. This comparison can be displayed through Mead’s overall concept of experience through the mind and James’ concept of the “social self.” In Mead’s article The Self The I and The Me he states that “What determines the amount of the self that gets into communication is the social experience itself.” What Mead is trying to express in this quote is that the way we express ourselves based on our previous experiences and that whether we allow ourselves to come through fully or not depends on how comfortable we are at a given time/conversation. This concept is extremely comparable to James’ specific connotation of the “social self” with both ideas referring to how we express ourselves and are perceived by others based on experiences.  “The amount of the self that gets into conversation…” can be viewed as the differing degrees of personality we express at any given time based on the conversation and comfortability.

Mead states that our environment determines the amount of the self we express while James argues this expression is merely a third of the overall construct. Either way these similarities in ideas shows that although the two sociologists have differing ideas on the self, their concepts can still go along with and support the other if analyzed properly.
